The African American story

74
00:03:35,048 --> 00:03:38,540
begins here,
on the Atlantic Ocean.

75
00:03:39,953 --> 00:03:42,012
Africans crossed these waters

76
00:03:42,088 --> 00:03:45,353
with the very first
European explorers.

77
00:03:45,425 --> 00:03:48,485
And their stories show that
right from the start,

78
00:03:48,561 --> 00:03:50,961
the black people who came
to this land

79
00:03:51,030 --> 00:03:54,466
nurtured aspirations
and dreams...

80
00:03:55,768 --> 00:03:57,360
dreams that would never
disappear,

81
00:03:57,437 --> 00:04:01,498
even in the long night
of slavery...

82
00:04:01,574 --> 00:04:05,408
dreams that would help them
endure and overcome.

83
00:04:13,253 --> 00:04:17,622
Florida. The first known
African in America

84
00:04:17,690 --> 00:04:22,150
came here with Spanish
explorers in 1513.

85
00:04:24,330 --> 00:04:27,231
His name was Juan Garrido.

86
00:04:27,300 --> 00:04:31,703
He was free, and he left
his mark on the New World.

87
00:04:31,771 --> 00:04:35,070
Garrido helped Cortez
take Mexico.

88
00:04:35,141 --> 00:04:39,077
Then he headed for California,
searching for gold.

89
00:04:44,550 --> 00:04:45,983
20 years later,

90
00:04:46,052 --> 00:04:49,988
a black man struggled to
cross this Texas desert.

91
00:04:52,925 --> 00:04:55,086
He was called Esteban the Moor.

92
00:04:57,130 --> 00:05:01,692
He was one of just 4 survivors
of a Spanish expedition

93
00:05:01,768 --> 00:05:04,134
that went horribly wrong.

94
00:05:05,605 --> 00:05:08,335
Esteban served as a guide
and a translator

95
00:05:08,408 --> 00:05:12,276
for his companions, negotiating
their way to safety

96
00:05:12,345 --> 00:05:15,940
across this forbidding
landscape.

97
00:05:16,015 --> 00:05:20,611
By the year 1536, they had
walked 15,000 miles.

98
00:05:20,687 --> 00:05:23,520
They had seen more of
the North American continent

99
00:05:23,589 --> 00:05:28,253
than any explorers would
until Lewis and Clark.

100
00:05:28,328 --> 00:05:29,920
GATES, VOICE-OVER:
Garrido and Esteban

101
00:05:29,996 --> 00:05:34,126
were among the first Africans
in our country.

102
00:05:34,200 --> 00:05:36,760
They found hope
and opportunity here.

103
00:05:38,137 --> 00:05:40,867
But things changed quickly.

104
00:05:50,049 --> 00:05:53,541
Jamestown, Virginia--
the first British colony

105
00:05:53,619 --> 00:05:57,077
in what became
the United States.

106
00:05:57,156 --> 00:06:02,025
In 1619, this was
the ultimate frontier town,

107
00:06:02,095 --> 00:06:06,862
crude fortifications bordering
a muddy malarial swamp.

108
00:06:06,933 --> 00:06:11,427
Then one morning in August,
a ship appeared-

109
00:06:11,504 --> 00:06:14,371
the "White Lion."

110
00:06:14,440 --> 00:06:19,241
It was a pirate ship
carrying African slaves.

111
00:06:19,312 --> 00:06:24,011
Roughly 20 of them
were traded here for food.

112
00:06:24,083 --> 00:06:28,042
That's how slavery began
in the English colonies.

113
00:06:29,455 --> 00:06:34,825
Plantations, as we imagine them,
didn't exist yet.

114
00:06:34,894 --> 00:06:38,660
This was just a fragile outpost
in the wilderness.

115
00:06:41,768 --> 00:06:43,065
MAN: Lives in
colonial Virginia

116
00:06:43,136 --> 00:06:44,433
were very precarious.

117
00:06:44,504 --> 00:06:48,634
They were really stuck
at the edge of survival.

118
00:06:48,708 --> 00:06:50,767
GATES, VOICE-OVER:
I've come here,

119
00:06:50,843 --> 00:06:53,437
just a few miles from Jamestown,

120
00:06:53,513 --> 00:06:57,711
to look for traces of a man
named Anthony Johnson,

121
00:06:57,784 --> 00:07:03,518
a man whose life shows how
slavery evolved in Virginia.

122
00:07:03,589 --> 00:07:05,853
SWEET: Our first notation
of Anthony Johnson

123
00:07:05,925 --> 00:07:08,086
is from the early Virginia
muster roll,

124
00:07:08,161 --> 00:07:09,355
which essentially
defines him

125
00:07:09,429 --> 00:07:10,953
as Antonio the Negro.

126
00:07:11,030 --> 00:07:12,588
So his blackness
was pan of his name,

127
00:07:12,665 --> 00:07:13,632
his title.

128
00:07:13,699 --> 00:07:16,259
Exactly.

129
00:07:16,335 --> 00:07:18,064
GATES, VOICE-OVER:
Despite his skin color,

130
00:07:18,137 --> 00:07:21,595
Johnson found opportunities
in Jamestown.

131
00:07:21,674 --> 00:07:24,234
He worked side by side
with his owner

132
00:07:24,310 --> 00:07:28,041
and forged a bond
based on necessity

133
00:07:28,114 --> 00:07:29,103
SWEET: In order for
the master to survive,

134
00:07:29,182 --> 00:07:31,343
he needed Anthony Johnson.

135
00:07:31,417 --> 00:07:33,214
To make a farm in this
kind of environment,

136
00:07:33,286 --> 00:07:34,878
it was all about
manual labor,

137
00:07:34,954 --> 00:07:37,354
so Anthony Johnson
earned his way

138
00:07:37,423 --> 00:07:40,586
to his own freedom,
and his master actually

139
00:07:40,660 --> 00:07:43,060
provided him with son of
a start-up, if you will.

140
00:07:43,129 --> 00:07:45,063
He gave him a little
cash, some land?

141
00:07:45,131 --> 00:07:47,691
Yeah, some land,
it seems. Yes.

142
00:07:50,203 --> 00:07:55,038
GATES, VOICE-OVER:
Anthony Johnson soon
began to prosper.

143
00:07:55,107 --> 00:07:58,440
He owned a 250-acre
tobacco farm,

144
00:07:58,511 --> 00:08:01,139
he had white indentured
servants,

145
00:08:01,214 --> 00:08:04,809
and he even had an African
slave of his own.

146
00:08:07,487 --> 00:08:11,719
But as Johnson prospered,
so did Virginia.

147
00:08:11,791 --> 00:08:14,726
Within decades, Jamestown
had become the center

148
00:08:14,794 --> 00:08:17,126
of a booming tobacco economy

149
00:08:17,196 --> 00:08:19,926
that was desperate for labor,

150
00:08:19,999 --> 00:08:22,866
and this transformed slavery

151
00:08:22,935 --> 00:08:25,563
from a loose, informal
arrangement

152
00:08:25,638 --> 00:08:29,074
into a rigid racial system,
a system in which

153
00:08:29,141 --> 00:08:33,134
a life like Anthony Johnson's
would be inconceivable.

154
00:08:33,212 --> 00:08:35,476
SWEET: Johnson's blackness,
his African-ness,

155
00:08:35,548 --> 00:08:39,382
these things define him,
mark him as an outsider.

156
00:08:39,452 --> 00:08:40,384
The stigma
of blackness.

157
00:08:40,453 --> 00:08:41,442
The stigma
of blackness,

158
00:08:41,521 --> 00:08:44,490
and the fact that
the status was tied

159
00:08:44,557 --> 00:08:48,391
to that observable
trait was one which was
very difficult to surmount.

160
00:08:49,929 --> 00:08:51,487
GATES: After Johnson died,

161
00:08:51,564 --> 00:08:55,193
a noun ruled that he
was "a negroe"

162
00:08:55,268 --> 00:08:59,432
and by consequence an "alien."

163
00:08:59,505 --> 00:09:04,067
And then the colony of Virginia
seized his family's land.

164
00:09:09,649 --> 00:09:14,643
Johnson's story marked a new era
in the British colonies.

165
00:09:14,720 --> 00:09:21,091
From this point on, slavery
would be solely based on race,

166
00:09:21,160 --> 00:09:24,254
and the acquisition of slaves
would be central

167
00:09:24,330 --> 00:09:27,322
to the acquisition of wealth.

168
00:09:27,400 --> 00:09:31,166
In effect, the British were
simply trying to do

169
00:09:31,237 --> 00:09:34,729
what many Europeans
had already done.

170
00:09:38,911 --> 00:09:41,573
By the time Anthony Johnson
arrived in Jamestown

171
00:09:41,647 --> 00:09:46,675
in the early 1620s, more than
half a million enslaved Africans

172
00:09:46,752 --> 00:09:49,778
had already been spread
across the New World

173
00:09:49,855 --> 00:09:54,155
into Brazil, Mexico,
and the Caribbean.

174
00:09:54,226 --> 00:09:58,686
The free labor of these slaves
was making fortunes

175
00:09:58,764 --> 00:10:01,892
for the Portuguese
and the Spanish.

176
00:10:01,968 --> 00:10:05,961
Now the British wanted
to get in on the action.

177
00:10:06,038 --> 00:10:07,767
SWEET: Most of the largest
cities of the Americas

178
00:10:07,840 --> 00:10:09,205
were dominated
by Africans.

179
00:10:09,275 --> 00:10:10,833
There were more Africans
in those cities

180
00:10:10,910 --> 00:10:12,309
than there were Europeans.

181
00:10:12,378 --> 00:10:15,814
SWEET: Here I'm talking about
places like Mexico City, Lima,

182
00:10:15,881 --> 00:10:17,849
Panama City, Havana.

183
00:10:17,917 --> 00:10:20,249
So when Jamestown is founded,

184
00:10:20,319 --> 00:10:23,720
all of those colonists
understood

185
00:10:23,789 --> 00:10:26,986
a wold in which Africans
were the primary labor force

186
00:10:27,059 --> 00:10:29,084
for producing wealth for Europe.

187
00:10:29,161 --> 00:10:30,219
I think it's important
to understand

188
00:10:30,296 --> 00:10:31,763
that the British
are not innovating

189
00:10:31,831 --> 00:10:33,093
when they settle Jamestown.

190
00:10:33,165 --> 00:10:35,326
They're trying to catch up.

191
00:10:35,401 --> 00:10:37,733
BROWN: American historians
sometimes treat

192
00:10:37,803 --> 00:10:40,237
the emergence of slavery
as a mystery

193
00:10:40,306 --> 00:10:41,238
where all of a sudden people go,

194
00:10:41,307 --> 00:10:43,036
"How did all these
Africans get here?"

195
00:10:43,109 --> 00:10:44,633
The real mystery would have been

196
00:10:44,710 --> 00:10:47,543
if slavery had not
developed in Virginia.

197
00:10:49,015 --> 00:10:52,610
GATES: A brutal equation
ruled the New World:

198
00:10:52,685 --> 00:10:56,382
black equaled slave.

199
00:10:56,455 --> 00:10:59,117
And to fulfill
their hunger for slaves,

200
00:10:59,191 --> 00:11:02,319
the British turned to the place
that many other Europeans

201
00:11:02,395 --> 00:11:04,663
had turned already: Africa.

202
00:11:04,664 --> 00:11:05,460
Had turned already: Africa.

203
00:11:09,669 --> 00:11:15,107
Sierra Leone was once
a major hub for the slave trade.

204
00:11:15,174 --> 00:11:19,338
More than 300,000 people
were taken from here

205
00:11:19,412 --> 00:11:22,142
and shipped to the New World
in bondage.

206
00:11:22,214 --> 00:11:26,947
But the first slave traders
in this place weren't Europeans.

207
00:11:27,019 --> 00:11:29,954
They were other black Africans.

208
00:11:34,960 --> 00:11:36,860
Africans practiced slavery

209
00:11:36,929 --> 00:11:41,423
long before they ever
saw a white person.

210
00:11:41,500 --> 00:11:43,024
All across this continent,

211
00:11:43,102 --> 00:11:46,469
slaves were pan of a system
based not on race,

212
00:11:46,539 --> 00:11:49,997
but on ethnic difference
and brute power,

213
00:11:50,076 --> 00:11:51,873
a system involving
an enormous array

214
00:11:51,944 --> 00:11:55,641
of monarchs, merchants,
and mercenaries.

215
00:11:55,715 --> 00:11:58,548
WOMAN:African kingdoms were at
war with one another.

216
00:11:58,617 --> 00:12:01,415
War was a theme in Africa,
and actually Europe as well,

217
00:12:01,487 --> 00:12:03,478
for many, many years, and so

218
00:12:03,556 --> 00:12:06,218
as a pan of these wars,
as a result of these wars,

219
00:12:06,292 --> 00:12:09,784
people were taken hostage
and made into slaves.

220
00:12:14,200 --> 00:12:16,430
GATES, VOICE-OVER:
I've come to Port Loko,

221
00:12:16,502 --> 00:12:20,438
a river town in Sierra Leone,
and the longstanding home

222
00:12:20,506 --> 00:12:22,303
of the Temne people.

223
00:12:25,845 --> 00:12:29,110
For centuries, the Temne here
collected captives

224
00:12:29,181 --> 00:12:31,615
who had been taken in wars.

225
00:12:31,684 --> 00:12:35,120
They tied them, packed them
into small boats,

226
00:12:35,187 --> 00:12:37,212
and sailed them downstream,

227
00:12:37,289 --> 00:12:40,417
where they were sold
to Europeans for profit.

228
00:12:42,628 --> 00:12:45,563
We sometimes romanticize Africa.

229
00:12:45,631 --> 00:12:50,034
We think that Africa was idyllic
until the white man came.

230
00:12:50,102 --> 00:12:54,766
But there were deep tensions
between ethnic groups here.

231
00:12:54,840 --> 00:12:58,606
Black Africans didn't
necessarily feel the bonds

232
00:12:58,677 --> 00:13:05,981
of skin color any more strongly
than, say, white Europeans did.

233
00:13:06,051 --> 00:13:10,351
