00:13:57,203 --> 00:13:59,671
and some of them were
willing to tell me about it.

253
00:13:59,738 --> 00:14:02,263
Good. Speak
from your heart.

254
00:14:02,341 --> 00:14:04,536
[Translator speaking
African language]

255
00:14:04,610 --> 00:14:06,544
GATES: Did any of you
receive wealth

256
00:14:06,612 --> 00:14:08,603
inherited from
the slave trade?

257
00:14:16,822 --> 00:14:17,811
500?
500.

258
00:14:17,890 --> 00:14:19,983
[Whistles]
My God. So he
was very rich.

259
00:14:20,059 --> 00:14:24,257
Yes. Yes, our people
were rich.

260
00:14:33,405 --> 00:14:37,671
Would chiefs wage war
just to get slaves?

261
00:14:37,743 --> 00:14:38,732
Oh, yes.

262
00:14:47,753 --> 00:14:50,153
In America,
we think black men

263
00:14:50,222 --> 00:14:52,713
were selling
black people
to the white man,

264
00:14:52,791 --> 00:14:55,487
but when you see it,
do you see it as

265
00:14:55,561 --> 00:14:58,462
Temne were
buying Loko--

266
00:14:58,530 --> 00:15:02,057
Mende were buying
Temne, at cetera.

267
00:15:02,134 --> 00:15:03,396
Is there
a difference?

268
00:15:03,469 --> 00:15:04,401
Well--

269
00:15:04,470 --> 00:15:05,801
Were all black
people black?

270
00:15:05,871 --> 00:15:07,133
[Speaking
African language]

271
00:15:07,206 --> 00:15:09,834
TRANSLATOR:
[indistinct] who are black.

272
00:15:09,909 --> 00:15:13,401
We don't speak
the same language.

273
00:15:13,479 --> 00:15:17,381
I don't like
what you like.

274
00:15:17,449 --> 00:15:19,974
You know, we don't
just live in harmony.

275
00:15:23,155 --> 00:15:25,385
GATES: Though some find it
difficult to face,

276
00:15:25,457 --> 00:15:28,358
the crucial role of Africans
in the slave trade

277
00:15:28,427 --> 00:15:31,863
is now well-documented.

278
00:15:31,931 --> 00:15:33,626
Historians estimate that

279
00:15:33,699 --> 00:15:36,293
the overwhelming majority
of the slaves

280
00:15:36,368 --> 00:15:40,202
shipped to the New World
were captured and sold

281
00:15:40,272 --> 00:15:41,940
by African kingdoms.

282
00:15:41,941 --> 00:15:43,033
By African kingdoms.

283
00:15:43,108 --> 00:15:46,168
But Africans did not
invent slavery.

284
00:15:46,245 --> 00:15:47,837
It existed everywhere,

285
00:15:47,913 --> 00:15:51,542
dating back to the most
ancient civilizations.

286
00:15:53,052 --> 00:15:55,577
Nor did Africans
envision slavery

287
00:15:55,654 --> 00:15:57,952
as something that
would be passed on

288
00:15:58,023 --> 00:16:00,753
from one generation
to the next,

289
00:16:00,826 --> 00:16:05,092
something based
exclusively on race.

290
00:16:05,164 --> 00:16:08,759
That was a European innovation.

291
00:16:08,834 --> 00:16:11,803
BROWN: Europeans had actually
developed an idea,

292
00:16:11,870 --> 00:16:13,098
Over several centuries,

293
00:16:13,172 --> 00:16:15,197
that they should not
enslave each other.

294
00:16:15,274 --> 00:16:17,139
They could kill each other,
torture each other,

295
00:16:17,209 --> 00:16:18,836
fight each other in wars,

296
00:16:18,911 --> 00:16:21,379
but Europeans did not
enslave other Europeans

297
00:16:21,447 --> 00:16:24,610
because Christians did not
enslave other Christians.

298
00:16:24,683 --> 00:16:27,516
The great advantage of Africans
is that they were outside

299
00:16:27,586 --> 00:16:30,783
the European community,
and so it was possible

300
00:16:30,856 --> 00:16:34,189
to use race as away
of providing a marker

301
00:16:34,259 --> 00:16:36,386
of who's enslavable
and who's not.

302
00:16:38,430 --> 00:16:40,557
GATES: Sailing in ships
of radical new design,

303
00:16:40,632 --> 00:16:44,329
armed with new weapons
and new technologies,

304
00:16:44,403 --> 00:16:48,897
Europeans transform slavery
into a business far larger

305
00:16:48,974 --> 00:16:53,741
and far crueler than anything
the Africans had ever done.

306
00:16:55,848 --> 00:16:59,477
Of course, it didn't
happen overnight.

307
00:16:59,551 --> 00:17:02,543
The dehumanization
of an entire race

308
00:17:02,621 --> 00:17:06,819
was a process requiring
many steps.

309
00:17:06,892 --> 00:17:10,350
One occurred here.

310
00:17:10,429 --> 00:17:14,092
This beautiful island
shrouded in fog

311
00:17:14,166 --> 00:17:17,329
is home to what was once
a fortress built by the British

312
00:17:17,403 --> 00:17:19,803
in the 1670s.

313
00:17:19,872 --> 00:17:22,670
WOMAN: Out there is
the mouth of the
Port Loko Creek.

314
00:17:22,741 --> 00:17:25,005
African middlemen used
to bring their slaves

315
00:17:25,077 --> 00:17:27,409
and goods down
the Port Loko Creek

316
00:17:27,479 --> 00:17:29,674
through the mouth
of the Port Loko Creek
out there

317
00:17:29,748 --> 00:17:31,409
all the way to this
beach here.

318
00:17:31,483 --> 00:17:33,007
So they came
right through
that gap right there.

319
00:17:33,085 --> 00:17:34,074
Yes, sir. Yes.

320
00:17:34,153 --> 00:17:35,415
GATES: They would
bring them here.

321
00:17:35,487 --> 00:17:36,852
They'd march them
straight up there
and sell them.

322
00:17:36,922 --> 00:17:39,823
Up this hill up on to
the trading area.

323
00:17:41,593 --> 00:17:43,652
GATES, VOICE-OVER: Though its
walls have long crumbled,

324
00:17:43,729 --> 00:17:47,825
I could still get a sense of how
this place once worked.

325
00:17:47,900 --> 00:17:50,334
SMITH: This was
the main entrance
into the fort.

326
00:17:50,402 --> 00:17:52,495
It had a double
folding door

327
00:17:52,571 --> 00:17:55,506
with a little
[indistinct] patch
on top.

328
00:17:55,574 --> 00:17:57,235
GATES, VOICE-OVER: British
officers lived here,

329
00:17:57,309 --> 00:18:00,972
in a lavish two-story mansion.

330
00:18:01,046 --> 00:18:02,604
SMITH: That's
a fireplace,

331
00:18:02,681 --> 00:18:04,911
a fake fireplace because
there is no flue.

332
00:18:04,983 --> 00:18:06,075
This is the tropics.

333
00:18:06,151 --> 00:18:08,619
We don't need a fire
in the tropics.

334
00:18:08,687 --> 00:18:11,884
But it was an attempt
by the slave traders
that lived here

335
00:18:11,957 --> 00:18:13,390
at elegance.

336
00:18:13,459 --> 00:18:14,448
GATES: A little
touch of home.

337
00:18:14,526 --> 00:18:16,118
SMITH: A little
touch of home.

338
00:18:16,195 --> 00:18:18,755
GATES, VOICE-OVER: The British
enjoyed parties here,

339
00:18:18,831 --> 00:18:21,265
even a small golf course.

340
00:18:21,333 --> 00:18:24,825
Slaves, meanwhile, were
herded like cattle.

341
00:18:24,903 --> 00:18:28,395
SMITH: In here is the
women's and children's
slave yard.

342
00:18:28,474 --> 00:18:30,533
GATES, VOICE-OVER: They were
branded, then held in pens

343
00:18:30,609 --> 00:18:32,975
for shipment to the New World.

344
00:18:33,045 --> 00:18:34,171
So the men were
over there,

345
00:18:34,246 --> 00:18:35,406
and the women
and children were
right here.

346
00:18:35,481 --> 00:18:36,812
So they could hear
each other's cries.

347
00:18:36,882 --> 00:18:39,180
Definitely.
They could have heard
each other's cries,

348
00:18:39,251 --> 00:18:41,082
but they could not
help each other.

349
00:18:41,153 --> 00:18:43,121
In fact, let me show you
the men's slave yard.

350
00:18:43,188 --> 00:18:45,179
It's right through
these doors.

351
00:18:45,257 --> 00:18:46,189
By the time
they got here,

352
00:18:46,258 --> 00:18:48,021
they were very
terrified,

353
00:18:48,093 --> 00:18:50,391
and then they were
examined like cattle--

354
00:18:50,462 --> 00:18:54,421
their eyes, teeth-
and then when the slaves
were taken out

355
00:18:54,500 --> 00:18:56,764
to be put on board
the slave ships,

356
00:18:56,835 --> 00:18:59,736
they were branded
with the letter "s"
on their left breast

357
00:18:59,805 --> 00:19:02,706
to denote that they
came from Sierra Leone.

358
00:19:11,683 --> 00:19:14,243
GATES: This place
was not unusual.

359
00:19:14,319 --> 00:19:16,651
There were dozens
of forts like this

360
00:19:16,722 --> 00:19:20,249
up and down the African coast.

361
00:19:20,325 --> 00:19:21,815
We're not even sure exactly

362
00:19:21,894 --> 00:19:24,886
how many slaves passed
through this island-

363
00:19:24,963 --> 00:19:27,989
50,000 at least.

364
00:19:28,066 --> 00:19:30,500
We know the names of a handful

365
00:19:30,569 --> 00:19:33,732
and the stories
of a precious few.

366
00:19:40,579 --> 00:19:44,140
In 1756, a British ship
named the "Hare"

367
00:19:44,216 --> 00:19:46,309
set sail for Charleston

368
00:19:46,385 --> 00:19:49,548
carrying 80 African slaves-.

369
00:19:49,621 --> 00:19:52,454
One of them was
a 10-year-old girl.

370
00:19:52,524 --> 00:19:54,185
We don't know where
she was from.

371
00:19:54,259 --> 00:19:56,420
We don't know
her parents' names.

372
00:19:56,495 --> 00:20:00,795
But we do know the name
that her master gave her:

373
00:20:00,866 --> 00:20:02,731
Priscilla.

374
00:20:02,801 --> 00:20:05,634
SINGERS: "Wade °

375
00:20:05,704 --> 00:20:10,437
° In the water °

376
00:20:10,509 --> 00:20:13,501
n Wade n

377
00:20:13,579 --> 00:20:18,516
° In the water, children °

378
00:20:18,584 --> 00:20:21,417
n Wade n

379
00:20:21,486 --> 00:20:23,750
° In the water..."

380
00:20:23,822 --> 00:20:25,949
GATES: Priscilla was at
the start of a journey

381
00:20:26,024 --> 00:20:28,219
that would change
her life forever:

382
00:20:28,293 --> 00:20:30,318
the dreaded Middle Passage.

383
00:20:30,395 --> 00:20:36,391
SINGERS: ° The water °

384
00:20:36,468 --> 00:20:39,437
WOMAN: The entire experience
is so horrific

385
00:20:39,504 --> 00:20:45,773
and so just brutalizing in ways
that are just unimaginable

386
00:20:45,844 --> 00:20:48,540
for a contemporary audience.

387
00:20:50,349 --> 00:20:52,249
You have public floggings.

388
00:20:52,317 --> 00:20:54,751
You have decapitation.

389
00:20:54,820 --> 00:20:58,256
Being immersed in your own
bodily excrement.

390
00:20:58,323 --> 00:20:59,585
[Baby crying]

391
00:20:59,658 --> 00:21:02,024
It is complete loss
of control over your life

392
00:21:02,094 --> 00:21:04,585
in every way possible.

393
00:21:07,099 --> 00:21:11,763
Think about an 8-, a 9-,
a 10-year-old.

394
00:21:11,837 --> 00:21:13,896
It is something that you're
never going to forget,

395
00:21:13,972 --> 00:21:16,236
and it's going to be etched
in your memory.

396
00:21:17,843 --> 00:21:21,006
GATES: Women on the ship, even
girls as young as Priscilla,

397
00:21:21,079 --> 00:21:23,547
faced an added danger:

398
00:21:23,615 --> 00:21:28,052
they were completely at
the mercy of the male crew.

399
00:21:28,120 --> 00:21:31,214
MUSTAKEEM: Women were considered
to be available prey

400
00:21:31,290 --> 00:21:33,656
at any given moment
for the entire ship crew

401
00:21:33,725 --> 00:21:35,488
throughout the passage,

402
00:21:35,560 --> 00:21:38,552
so some women would
commit suicide,

403
00:21:38,630 --> 00:21:40,791
and some women did decide that

404
00:21:40,866 --> 00:21:43,266
"I don't want to bring a child
into this world,"

405
00:21:43,335 --> 00:21:46,270
so they inserted some
son of piece of wood

406
00:21:46,338 --> 00:21:50,172
or nail or something to,
you know, cause violence

407
00:21:50,242 --> 00:21:53,769
upon their body, and you will
also find that some women

408
00:21:53,845 --> 00:21:58,544
would actually die
from these attempts.

409
00:21:58,617 --> 00:22:03,418
GATES: Priscilla spent
10 weeks on the ship.

410
00:22:03,488 --> 00:22:07,549
She saw 13 of her fellow
Africans die along the way,

411
00:22:07,626 --> 00:22:11,153
their corpses thrown
into the ocean.

412
00:22:11,229 --> 00:22:13,561
Death was so common
on slave ships

413
00:22:13,632 --> 00:22:16,362
that sharks followed
in their wake,

414
00:22:16,435 --> 00:22:19,836
feasting on the dead bodies.

415
00:22:19,905 --> 00:22:21,964
[Thunder]

416
00:22:25,677 --> 00:22:27,838
As the ship drew close to shore,

417
00:22:27,913 --> 00:22:31,405
the slaves were rubbed with
a mixture of gunpowder and oil

418
00:22:31,483 --> 00:22:34,475
to make them look healthier,
hiding the wounds

419
00:22:34,553 --> 00:22:37,886
from their beatings and chains.

420
00:22:37,956 --> 00:22:41,359
Then Priscilla stepped
into a new world.

421
00:22:41,360 --> 00:22:42,054
Then Priscilla stepped
into a new world.

422
00:22:44,196 --> 00:22:46,892
Charleston, South Carolina.

423
00:22:46,965 --> 00:22:49,058
This was once the center
of the slave trade

424
00:22:49,134 --> 00:22:52,001
in the 13 colonies.

425
00:22:52,070 --> 00:22:55,733
Over 40% of all the slaves
who entered our country

426
00:22:55,807 --> 00:22:58,867
came through this city.

427
00:22:58,944 --> 00:23:02,778
In Priscilla's time, South
Carolina had more black slaves

428
00:23:02,848 --> 00:23:06,215
than white citizens.

429
00:23:06,284 --> 00:23:08,946
In fact, it was called
"Negro country."

430
00:23:09,020 --> 00:23:09,952
[Whip cracks]

431
00:23:10,021 --> 00:23:11,648
[Stamping]

432
00:23:11,723 --> 00:23:12,985
[Church bell rings]

433
00:23:13,058 --> 00:23:14,650
GATES: Slave auctions were held

434
00:23:14,726 --> 00:23:16,125
on the streets of Charleston

435
00:23:16,194 --> 00:23:17,855
almost every day.

436
00:23:19,197 --> 00:23:20,994
Priscilla was bought
at one of these auctions

437
00:23:21,066 --> 00:23:24,627
by a rice planter
named Elias Ball.

438
00:23:29,307 --> 00:23:31,741
MAN: We're on the way
to the Ball plantation,

439
00:23:31,810 --> 00:23:35,837
which consisted of
1/2 of Comingtee plantation

440
00:23:35,914 --> 00:23:38,644
and about 25 African
American slaves.

441
00:23:38,717 --> 00:23:42,153
GATES, VOICE-OVER: Edward Ball
is the fifth great-grandson

442
00:23:42,220 --> 00:23:45,212
of the man who purchased
Priscilla.

443
00:23:45,290 --> 00:23:47,224
He's brought me to the land

444
00:23:47,292 --> 00:23:49,283
where his family ran
rice plantations

445
00:23:49,361 --> 00:23:50,794
for almost two centuries.

446
00:23:50,862 --> 00:23:52,796
...the landlord
with a thousand acres.

447
00:23:52,864 --> 00:23:56,732
So this would have
been maybe one little
road running through it.

448
00:23:56,802 --> 00:24:00,363
Yeah. The rice fields
were off the river.

449
00:24:00,439 --> 00:24:02,430
They were
right around here.

450
00:24:02,507 --> 00:24:04,270
GATES, VOICE-OVER: Ball told me
he had spent years

451
00:24:04,342 --> 00:24:06,640
wrestling with
his family's past.

452
00:24:06,711 --> 00:24:11,171
Priscilla is just
one of 4,000 people
that they owned.

453
00:24:11,249 --> 00:24:14,082
My dad used to talk
about the plantations

454
00:24:14,152 --> 00:24:17,883
and Elias Ball
and all of the--

455
00:24:17,956 --> 00:24:23,758
the prosperity
that our family
had lived through,

456
00:24:23,829 --> 00:24:26,662
but he never talked
about the slaves.

457
00:24:26,731 --> 00:24:29,325
He said, "There are
5 things we don't
talk about

458
00:24:29,401 --> 00:24:31,028
"in the Ball family:

459
00:24:31,102 --> 00:24:36,631
religion, sex, death,
money, and the Negroes."

460
00:24:36,708 --> 00:24:38,437
[Gates laughs]

461
00:24:41,813 --> 00:24:46,580
GATES, VOICE-OVER: Priscilla
arrived herein July 1756.

462
00:24:48,286 --> 00:24:49,981
She was 10.

463
00:24:51,957 --> 00:24:54,118
BALL: She came
as an orphan--

464
00:24:54,192 --> 00:24:58,288
no parents,
no language, no home.

465
00:24:58,363 --> 00:25:01,298
This was her
introduction

466
00:25:01,366 --> 00:25:03,596
to the rest
of her life.

467
00:25:06,438 --> 00:25:07,996
GATES, VOICE-OVER:
Priscilla's new life

468
00:25:08,073 --> 00:25:12,976
centered around this house and
the white family that owned it.

469
00:25:13,044 --> 00:25:17,174
Though a ruin today, the Ball
plantation was once thriving,

470
00:25:17,249 --> 00:25:19,877
thanks to the labor
of its slaves.

471
00:25:19,951 --> 00:25:22,078
BALL: The second Elias,
who bought Priscilla,

472
00:25:22,153 --> 00:25:25,350
bought 6 children,
none of them older
than 10.

473
00:25:25,423 --> 00:25:27,687
He liked buying children.

474
00:25:27,759 --> 00:25:30,193
In fact, he wrote
a little memoir

475
00:25:30,262 --> 00:25:33,527
in which he said,
"Due two things
with your money:

476
00:25:33,598 --> 00:25:36,260
buy land and buy
young slaves."

477
00:25:36,334 --> 00:25:38,199
GATES: Hmm. Why?

478
00:25:38,270 --> 00:25:41,205
BALL: Better
long-term investment.

479
00:25:41,273 --> 00:25:42,865
The white folks lived here.

480
00:25:42,941 --> 00:25:45,705
The black folks lived
about 1/4 mile away.

481
00:25:45,777 --> 00:25:50,646
The rice fields were about
half a mile down that road,

482
00:25:50,715 --> 00:25:53,411
and that's where
all the work

483
00:25:53,485 --> 00:25:57,012
of producing the money
took place.

484
00:26:00,058 --> 00:26:03,858
GATES: Rica-that's why
Priscilla was here.

485
00:26:03,929 --> 00:26:06,830
Rice fields like these
were making a fortune

486
00:26:06,898 --> 00:26:08,195
for slave-owners.

487
00:26:09,501 --> 00:26:11,867
Don't let their beauty
fool you.

488
00:26:11,937 --> 00:26:14,371
These places were death traps.

489
00:26:15,840 --> 00:26:19,173
The swamp ground was
covered with snakes.

490
00:26:19,244 --> 00:26:24,648
The tropical air was filled
with malarial mosquitoes.

491
00:26:24,716 --> 00:26:27,378
1/3 of South Carolina's slaves

492
00:26:27,452 --> 00:26:30,046
died within a year
of their arrival,

493
00:26:30,121 --> 00:26:35,491
and nearly 2/3 of all children
were dead before they turned 16.

494
00:26:37,195 --> 00:26:39,288
But Priscilla beat the odds.

495
00:26:39,364 --> 00:26:43,027
She and her family survived.

496
00:26:49,307 --> 00:26:51,673
BALL: The Balls were
fanatical about
keeping records.

497
00:26:51,743 --> 00:26:54,940
They had books
that listed
the birthdays

498
00:26:55,013 --> 00:26:56,480
of all the slave
children,

499
00:26:56,548 --> 00:26:59,881
books that listed
the deaths of all
the slave adults,

500
00:26:59,951 --> 00:27:02,681
and all of this stuff
is collected in an archive

