00:38:07,385 --> 00:38:09,979
it inspired one of
the biggest slave revolts

748
00:38:10,054 --> 00:38:12,022
in the history of
the British colonies.

749
00:38:15,393 --> 00:38:17,623
It all started right here-

750
00:38:17,695 --> 00:38:20,823
the site of what was
once a general store

751
00:38:20,898 --> 00:38:22,422
called Hutchinson's.

752
00:38:22,500 --> 00:38:24,695
[Rattling]

753
00:38:24,769 --> 00:38:29,035
Sunday morning,
September 9, 1739.

754
00:38:29,106 --> 00:38:32,269
Hutchinson's Store
had been looted.

755
00:38:32,343 --> 00:38:35,176
Its guns and ammunition
had been stolen.

756
00:38:35,246 --> 00:38:38,340
Two shopkeepers lay dead,
their severed heads lying

757
00:38:38,416 --> 00:38:41,078
on the steps of the store.

758
00:38:41,152 --> 00:38:46,112
Plantations on either side
of the river were burning.

759
00:38:46,190 --> 00:38:50,650
An army was on the move-
an African army.

760
00:38:53,497 --> 00:38:55,226
They were headed for Fort Mose.

761
00:38:57,468 --> 00:39:02,064
They set out before dawn,
a group of roughly 20 men.

762
00:39:02,139 --> 00:39:03,731
Their tactics were simple.

763
00:39:03,808 --> 00:39:06,003
They surrounded plantations,

764
00:39:06,077 --> 00:39:07,544
then burned them to the ground.

765
00:39:09,213 --> 00:39:12,080
The ringleaders came from
the kingdom of Congo,

766
00:39:12,149 --> 00:39:15,050
a powerful African state.

767
00:39:15,119 --> 00:39:19,112
Some had military training,
and they had a plan.

768
00:39:20,691 --> 00:39:23,592
POWERS: The slaves marched
over to Pon Pon Road,

769
00:39:23,661 --> 00:39:26,892
which was a road that,
if you took it south,

770
00:39:26,964 --> 00:39:29,194
it would take you
down into Georgia,

771
00:39:29,266 --> 00:39:30,824
down into Savannah,

772
00:39:30,901 --> 00:39:33,927
and ultimately all the way
down to Florida.

773
00:39:34,004 --> 00:39:35,904
[Drumbeat]

774
00:39:37,208 --> 00:39:39,142
They were beating drums.

775
00:39:39,210 --> 00:39:43,078
Now, the beating of the drums
is terribly important, because

776
00:39:43,147 --> 00:39:45,581
that shows us that
they were attempting

777
00:39:45,649 --> 00:39:48,880
to draw other Africans
into their midst.

778
00:39:50,054 --> 00:39:51,214
GATES: By afternoon,

779
00:39:51,288 --> 00:39:54,621
the rebel army had grown
to nearly 100,

780
00:39:54,692 --> 00:39:57,183
and they kept moving south,

781
00:39:57,261 --> 00:39:59,821
along what today
is this highway,

782
00:39:59,897 --> 00:40:02,889
which still leads
from South Carolina to Florida.

783
00:40:05,870 --> 00:40:07,167
But they didn't make it.

784
00:40:10,741 --> 00:40:13,471
Just 20 miles
outside of Charleston,

785
00:40:13,544 --> 00:40:16,240
an armed militia
caught up with them

786
00:40:16,313 --> 00:40:19,680
in a clearing in these woods.

787
00:40:19,750 --> 00:40:23,117
The survivors faced
a gruesome fate.

788
00:40:23,187 --> 00:40:27,021
POWERS: A number of
the people who were--

789
00:40:27,091 --> 00:40:29,252
were captured,

790
00:40:29,326 --> 00:40:30,520
they'd be beheaded.

791
00:40:30,594 --> 00:40:32,721
Beheaded.
They would be beheaded

792
00:40:32,797 --> 00:40:36,028
by the militiamen,

793
00:40:36,100 --> 00:40:40,196
and as was
a usual practice

794
00:40:40,271 --> 00:40:41,704
during the time period,

795
00:40:41,772 --> 00:40:45,731
their severed heads were
placed on top of posts

796
00:40:45,810 --> 00:40:47,675
along the highway.

797
00:40:47,745 --> 00:40:49,372
So, right along here,
Yeah.

798
00:40:49,447 --> 00:40:51,142
We would've
seen the heads
Yes.

799
00:40:51,215 --> 00:40:53,183
Of these rebels.
Yes. That's right.

800
00:40:53,250 --> 00:40:55,650
And that was meant
to instill fear.

801
00:40:55,719 --> 00:40:59,348
Mm.
And to teach
a lesson

802
00:40:59,423 --> 00:41:00,890
to all who observe

803
00:41:00,958 --> 00:41:03,392
to try to
discourage people

804
00:41:03,461 --> 00:41:05,827
from-from
rebelling.

805
00:41:05,896 --> 00:41:09,263
This must have been
the planters
worst nightmare.

806
00:41:09,333 --> 00:41:11,028
It was. Absolutely.

807
00:41:11,101 --> 00:41:12,227
Worse than
the worst thing.

808
00:41:12,303 --> 00:41:15,864
They couldn't imagine
that these Congo Africans

809
00:41:15,940 --> 00:41:17,965
knew anything about
guns and ammunition.

810
00:41:18,042 --> 00:41:19,805
That's right.
That's right
That's right.

811
00:41:19,877 --> 00:41:21,970
Absolutely right.
This was

812
00:41:22,046 --> 00:41:25,709
the worst
insurrection
to occur

813
00:41:25,783 --> 00:41:28,877
in 18th-century
British

814
00:41:28,953 --> 00:41:30,682
colonial
North America.
Huh.

815
00:41:33,591 --> 00:41:35,320
GATES: In the wake
of the rebellion,

816
00:41:35,392 --> 00:41:38,953
South Carolina imposed
harsh new slave laws.

817
00:41:39,029 --> 00:41:41,122
They banned drumming
and literacy,

818
00:41:41,198 --> 00:41:43,894
and set drastic punishments
on runaways.

819
00:41:45,669 --> 00:41:48,934
But no laws ever
could force the slaves

820
00:41:49,006 --> 00:41:50,598
to accept their fates.

821
00:41:58,382 --> 00:42:01,510
Slaves plotted revolts
all over the Atlantic world.

822
00:42:03,754 --> 00:42:07,451
In Jamaica, in Virginia,
Barbados and Georgia,

823
00:42:07,525 --> 00:42:08,992
even in New York City.

824
00:42:10,594 --> 00:42:11,891
Most of them failed.

825
00:42:13,597 --> 00:42:16,430
But that didn't stop
the slaves from trying.

826
00:42:16,500 --> 00:42:20,869
They were always searching
for a chance at freedom.

827
00:42:20,938 --> 00:42:25,042
And as time passed, freedom
seemed to be drawing near.

828
00:42:25,042 --> 00:42:25,531
And as time passed, freedom
seemed to be drawing near.

829
00:42:30,047 --> 00:42:33,778
The American Revolution brought
immense hope to the slaves.

830
00:42:33,851 --> 00:42:38,015
They heard the patriots
talk of liberty and equality,

831
00:42:38,088 --> 00:42:40,784
and it ignited their own dreams.

832
00:42:40,858 --> 00:42:44,760
But for the most pan,
those dreams were ignored.

833
00:42:46,130 --> 00:42:48,530
Even the greatest
champion of freedom

834
00:42:48,599 --> 00:42:51,067
was hesitant to extend it
to black people.

835
00:42:55,205 --> 00:42:59,164
This is Mount Vernon,
George Washington's estate.

836
00:42:59,243 --> 00:43:03,407
For so many of us, an icon of
American independence.

837
00:43:03,480 --> 00:43:06,472
But for more than
100 African Americans,

838
00:43:06,550 --> 00:43:08,279
this was a plantation,

839
00:43:08,352 --> 00:43:11,981
where from sunup to sundown,
they toiled as slaves.

840
00:43:17,528 --> 00:43:20,656
The father of our country
was also one of its

841
00:43:20,731 --> 00:43:22,596
largest slave owners.

842
00:43:24,034 --> 00:43:26,969
Slaves tended his fields

843
00:43:27,037 --> 00:43:29,301
and watched over his every need.

844
00:43:30,708 --> 00:43:32,699
One worked in these stables,

845
00:43:32,776 --> 00:43:36,507
a groomsman named
Harry Washington.

846
00:43:36,580 --> 00:43:38,480
Harry heard the talk
around Mount Vernon

847
00:43:38,549 --> 00:43:40,813
about liberty and independence,

848
00:43:40,884 --> 00:43:44,445
but he sensed it wasn't
meant for slaves.

849
00:43:44,521 --> 00:43:46,614
So, like many black people,

850
00:43:46,690 --> 00:43:50,854
he decided to take his chances
with the British.

851
00:43:50,928 --> 00:43:55,194
Once the war comes, there are
enslaved men and women saying,

852
00:43:55,265 --> 00:43:57,529
"Hey, we'd love to help you out

853
00:43:57,601 --> 00:43:59,831
"if you would help us out.

854
00:43:59,903 --> 00:44:03,839
"We'd be happy
